## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Thread.Abort to Cooperative Cancellation

### Pattern Classification: **Timeout Enforcement**

Your code uses `Thread.Abort()` to kill a thread that exceeds a time limit. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`). The replacement is cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(),   // legacy overload — work ignores the token
            timeout);
    }

    // Preferred overload: work cooperates with cancellation
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Unwrap AggregateException to surface the original exception
        if (task.IsFaulted)
            throw new AggregateException(task.Exception!.InnerExceptions);

        return task.Result;
    }
}
```

---

### What Changed and Why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Task-based model; avoids manual thread management |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(cts.Token)` | Cancellable wait (.NET 6+ API) |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (automatic via timeout) | Cooperative cancellation — the only option in modern .NET |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | No equivalent needed; cancellation is opt-in |

---

### Critical Pitfall: Uncooperative Work Won't Stop

The `Func<T>` overload wraps legacy work that **ignores** the token. The task's thread keeps running after timeout — it just becomes orphaned. This is the fundamental tradeoff:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  .NET Framework: Thread.Abort() forcibly kills the      │
│  thread (preemptive). Dangerous but immediate.          │
│                                                         │
│  .NET 8: CancellationToken requests cancellation        │
│  (cooperative). Safe but the work must check the token. │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**To get real cancellation**, pass work that checks the token:

```csharp
// ✅ Work cooperates — cancellation actually stops it
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        ProcessItem(item);
    }
    return ComputeResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| Forgetting to `Dispose` the `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks internal timers. Always use `using`. |
| Not passing token through the full call chain | If a nested method ignores the token, cancellation stalls at that point. |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| Truly uncooperative code (native calls, third-party libs) | Move to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` — the only safe forced termination in modern .NET. |
